{"title_page": "Maryam Amid", "text_new": "Venugopala Swamy temple yerrabalem-wikipedia<mapframe latitude=\"16.299051\" longitude=\"80.351257\" zoom=\"2\" width=\"200\" height=\"100\" align=\"right\" /><gallery>\nFile:Fort Pierce Inlet Fort Pierce Florida photo D Ramey Logan.jpg\n</gallery>\n\n= {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}venugopala Swamy temple yerrabalem-wikipedia =\n{{copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n'''Venugopala Swamy temple yerrabalem, Mangalagiri mandal Guntur district Andhra Pradesh.'''({{lang-fa|Venugopala Swamy temple}}) \n\nlf.<ref> Truth, Abdul Rafiee. The first female journalist in Iran, Ghohar, numbers 11\u201312 (December 1973 \u2013 January 1974) .</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nMaryam Amid Semnani published a [[women's magazine]] named ''Shokoufeh''. Shokoufeh Provided the opportunity for women and girls to be trained and informed about [[Women's rights|equal rights]] for both women and men. Additionally, Maryam established two branches of a modern school named Dokhtaran Dar al-'Elm and Sanayeh Mazineyeh. She was also a member of the [[Women's rights in Iran|Women's Rights]] Activists Association, which promoted the use of domestic goods and encouraged the acquisition of handicrafts by women. She translated several French books into [[Persian language]].\n\n== The establishment of a girls\u2019 school ==\nThe establishment of a [[Single-sex education|girls' school]] was one of the lasting and enduring works of Maryam Amid. In 1951, she founded a girls' school called Mazineyeh.\n\nDue to patriarchal circumstances and the reluctance of families to educate the girls, she encouraged girls to register to become a student without paying the student registration fee, this was done with one out of every two student and she agreed with their parents and families that they should study and not be taken out of school till the end of their courses. This was the way she encouraged girls to stay in school and study. The school had two branches. One of the branches was Dar al-'Elm and various sciences (Such as reading and writing to mathematics and geography and foreign language training) which were taught, and the condition of admission and degree was a test and test success that was held by the Ministry of Education. This school was located beside the garden of Asfal-Dooleh. The second branch, Dar Al- Sanayeh, was located in Abmangel neighborhood, teaching works of art and [[Handicraft]]s (Carpet [[weaving]], [[knitting]], etc.).<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.beytoote.com/scientific/scientist/first-1woman1-journalist.html  The biography of the first female Iranian journalist]</ref>\n\n== First Iranian woman journalist ==\nIn a time where reading and writing was uncommon for women and the education of women was largely frowned upon, Maryam was able to launch the first Iranian [[women's magazine]]. This 8-page weekly magazine, known as Science, published in [[Tehran]] in 1910. Although the magazine did not last long, it was an important development during the Constitutional era. \n\nMaryam Amid, known as the first female journalist in Iran, published the Shokoufeh Newspaper after the closure of the Science Weekly Magazine in 1913.\n\nThe following text was seen on the front page and certification of the journal:<ref name=\":0\" />\n{{quote|Awarding officer and director Maryam Amid, the daughter of the late Aqa Mirza Sayed Razi, was a journalist of ethics, literature, hygiene, child care, direct professional education of maidens, and the refinement of women's ethics about women's schools. Sometimes these were known in two levels.}}\n\n== Shokoufeh Newspaper ==\nThe ''Shokoufeh Newspaper'' was the second biggest dedicated newspaper published for women after the Science Magazine (1910\u20131911) in 1913. This newspaper was published every week till the death of Maryam in 1919.\n\nThe features of this newspaper could be mentioned in a [[Humour|humorous]] and critical tone, such as addressing Iranian women's issues, [[Girls education|girls' education]], and political issues.\n\n=== From copies to caricaturing\t===\nThe newspaper, which was published almost every two weeks, was originally written in four pages with the Traditional version writing of [[Naskh (script)|Naskhs]], but from the fifth issue was written with the [[Nasta\u02bfl\u012bq script|Nastaliq]] version, and was printed after a year with lead letters. Also on the final page of each issue it was decorated with a [[caricature]], tailored to the subject of the page that the issue was about.  Of course, from the third year and onwards, the caricatures were not included, since the publication lost its pattern at the start of the [[First World War]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Hemat Association ==\nHemat Association was established in 1944 by the managers of the girls\u2019 schools. Maryam Amid, a member of this association, was instrumental in introducing and expanding its activities. One of the important goals of the association, which was headed by Mrs. Nuraldji, was to ban foreign products and prohibit imports of these products. For example, at the same time, the boycott of foreign textiles was on the agenda of this association, and all girls' schools (including students and teachers) were allowed to use only Iranian fabrics and, if there was a violation and purchase of foreign textiles, the guilty person would be fired. Therefore, it came to a result that nearly five thousand people joined the boycott within a month. \n\n== War with superstition ==\nThe struggle against [[superstition]] and fighting with old traditions especially among women was one of the actions of Maryam. She used the ''Shokoufeh newspaper'' to convey the voice of suppression and reactionary ideas. Maryam, in condemning the women's [[underdeveloped]] traditions in [[Iran]], reviewed and raised the situation of women in other parts of the world (especially the situation of [[women in Europe]]), and considered this as the most important and [[Fundamentalism|fundamental]] way of women's awareness in Iran.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Death ==\nMaryam died in September 1919 during a trip to her hometown [[Semnan, Iran|Semnan]], of a heart attack. \n \n==See also==\n* [[Iranian women]]   \n* [[Women's rights movement in Iran]]\n* [[Women's rights in Iran]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* \u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af \u0642\u0648\u0645\u0633\u061b \u0641\u0635\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0645\u0647 \u067e\u0698\u0648\u0647\u0634\u06cc\u060c \u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af\u06cc\u060c \u0647\u0646\u0631\u06cc \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0633\u0645\u0646\u0627\u0646\u060c \u0634\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u06f3\u06f7 \u0648 \u06f3\u06f8 \u0628\u0647\u0627\u0631 \u0648 \u062a\u0627\u0628\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u06f1\u06f3\u06f8\u06f6/Ghomis Culture, The quarterly research of cultural and artistic in Semnan Province, numbers 37\u201338, spring and summer 2007.\n* \u0631\u0648\u0632\u0646\u0627\u0645\u0647 \u0633\u0631\u0645\u0627\u06cc\u0647\u060c \u0634\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u06f2\u06f5\u06f7 (\u06f2 \u0634\u0647\u0631\u06cc\u0648\u0631 \u06f1\u06f3\u06f8\u06f5)-\tSarmayeh Newspaper, number 257, (24 August 2006). \n* [http://www.sharghnewspaper.ir/830514/media.htm#s94047 /Journalist women under the shadow of constitutionalism]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.barnameh-budjeh.com/npview.asp?ID=1118573 Maryam Amid, Girls' Literacy Light]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amid, Maryam}}\n[[Category:People from Semnan, Iran]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:Iranian journalists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women journalists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n'''Maryam Amid Semnani''' ({{lang-fa|\u0645\u0631\u06cc\u0645 \u0639\u0645\u06cc\u062f \u0633\u0645\u0646\u0627\u0646\u06cc}}), was an intellectual and a journalist during the [[Qajar era]]. \nIn 1913, she published the second Iranian women's magazine named the ''Shokoufeh Newspaper''. \n\n== Biography ==\nMaryam Amid was the only daughter of Mir Seyed Razi Semnani, the first representative of [[Semnan, Iran|Semnan]] and [[Shahrud, Iran|Shahrud]] in the [[National Assembly]].  He was also known as \"Reyis Al-Atebah\", doctor of [[Naser al-Din Shah Qajar]] and Mirza Ibrahim Amid al-Saltanah. Maryam Amid was born in Semnan and studied primary education with her father. Later, she learned French and photography. At the age of 16, she married Hosseinfli Mirza Emad al-Saltanah Salvar, one of the princes during the Qajar period.  After only one year of marriage, Miryam secured a divorce. \n\nSeven years later, Maryam married a contemporary intellectual named Qawamul Hakmah. Seven years later, Qawamul died leaving Maryam to raise their two children by herself.<ref> Truth, Abdul Rafiee. The first female journalist in Iran, Ghohar, numbers 11\u201312 (December 1973 \u2013 January 1974) .</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\nMaryam Amid Semnani published a [[women's magazine]] named ''Shokoufeh''. Shokoufeh Provided the opportunity for women and girls to be trained and informed about [[Women's rights|equal rights]] for both women and men. Additionally, Maryam established two branches of a modern school named Dokhtaran Dar al-'Elm and Sanayeh Mazineyeh. She was also a member of the [[Women's rights in Iran|Women's Rights]] Activists Association, which promoted the use of domestic goods and encouraged the acquisition of handicrafts by women. She translated several French books into [[Persian language]].\n\n== The establishment of a girls\u2019 school ==\nThe establishment of a [[Single-sex education|girls' school]] was one of the lasting and enduring works of Maryam Amid. In 1951, she founded a girls' school called Mazineyeh.\n\nDue to patriarchal circumstances and the reluctance of families to educate the girls, she encouraged girls to register to become a student without paying the student registration fee, this was done with one out of every two student and she agreed with their parents and families that they should study and not be taken out of school till the end of their courses. This was the way she encouraged girls to stay in school and study. The school had two branches. One of the branches was Dar al-'Elm and various sciences (Such as reading and writing to mathematics and geography and foreign language training) which were taught, and the condition of admission and degree was a test and test success that was held by the Ministry of Education. This school was located beside the garden of Asfal-Dooleh. The second branch, Dar Al- Sanayeh, was located in Abmangel neighborhood, teaching works of art and [[Handicraft]]s (Carpet [[weaving]], [[knitting]], etc.).<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.beytoote.com/scientific/scientist/first-1woman1-journalist.html  The biography of the first female Iranian journalist]</ref>\n\n== First Iranian woman journalist ==\nIn a time where reading and writing was uncommon for women and the education of women was largely frowned upon, Maryam was able to launch the first Iranian [[women's magazine]]. This 8-page weekly magazine, known as Science, published in [[Tehran]] in 1910. Although the magazine did not last long, it was an important development during the Constitutional era. \n\nMaryam Amid, known as the first female journalist in Iran, published the Shokoufeh Newspaper after the closure of the Science Weekly Magazine in 1913.\n\nThe following text was seen on the front page and certification of the journal:<ref name=\":0\" />\n{{quote|Awarding officer and director Maryam Amid, the daughter of the late Aqa Mirza Sayed Razi, was a journalist of ethics, literature, hygiene, child care, direct professional education of maidens, and the refinement of women's ethics about women's schools. Sometimes these were known in two levels.}}\n\n== Shokoufeh Newspaper ==\nThe ''Shokoufeh Newspaper'' was the second biggest dedicated newspaper published for women after the Science Magazine (1910\u20131911) in 1913. This newspaper was published every week till the death of Maryam in 1919.\n\nThe features of this newspaper could be mentioned in a [[Humour|humorous]] and critical tone, such as addressing Iranian women's issues, [[Girls education|girls' education]], and political issues.\n\n=== From copies to caricaturing\t===\nThe newspaper, which was published almost every two weeks, was originally written in four pages with the Traditional version writing of [[Naskh (script)|Naskhs]], but from the fifth issue was written with the [[Nasta\u02bfl\u012bq script|Nastaliq]] version, and was printed after a year with lead letters. Also on the final page of each issue it was decorated with a [[caricature]], tailored to the subject of the page that the issue was about.  Of course, from the third year and onwards, the caricatures were not included, since the publication lost its pattern at the start of the [[First World War]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Hemat Association ==\nHemat Association was established in 1944 by the managers of the girls\u2019 schools. Maryam Amid, a member of this association, was instrumental in introducing and expanding its activities. One of the important goals of the association, which was headed by Mrs. Nuraldji, was to ban foreign products and prohibit imports of these products. For example, at the same time, the boycott of foreign textiles was on the agenda of this association, and all girls' schools (including students and teachers) were allowed to use only Iranian fabrics and, if there was a violation and purchase of foreign textiles, the guilty person would be fired. Therefore, it came to a result that nearly five thousand people joined the boycott within a month. \n\n== War with superstition ==\nThe struggle against [[superstition]] and fighting with old traditions especially among women was one of the actions of Maryam. She used the ''Shokoufeh newspaper'' to convey the voice of suppression and reactionary ideas. Maryam, in condemning the women's [[underdeveloped]] traditions in [[Iran]], reviewed and raised the situation of women in other parts of the world (especially the situation of [[women in Europe]]), and considered this as the most important and [[Fundamentalism|fundamental]] way of women's awareness in Iran.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n== Death ==\nMaryam died in September 1919 during a trip to her hometown [[Semnan, Iran|Semnan]], of a heart attack. \n \n==See also==\n* [[Iranian women]]   \n* [[Women's rights movement in Iran]]\n* [[Women's rights in Iran]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* \u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af \u0642\u0648\u0645\u0633\u061b \u0641\u0635\u0644\u0646\u0627\u0645\u0647 \u067e\u0698\u0648\u0647\u0634\u06cc\u060c \u0641\u0631\u0647\u0646\u06af\u06cc\u060c \u0647\u0646\u0631\u06cc \u0627\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u0633\u0645\u0646\u0627\u0646\u060c \u0634\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u06f3\u06f7 \u0648 \u06f3\u06f8 \u0628\u0647\u0627\u0631 \u0648 \u062a\u0627\u0628\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 \u06f1\u06f3\u06f8\u06f6/Ghomis Culture, The quarterly research of cultural and artistic in Semnan Province, numbers 37\u201338, spring and summer 2007.\n* \u0631\u0648\u0632\u0646\u0627\u0645\u0647 \u0633\u0631\u0645\u0627\u06cc\u0647\u060c \u0634\u0645\u0627\u0631\u0647 \u06f2\u06f5\u06f7 (\u06f2 \u0634\u0647\u0631\u06cc\u0648\u0631 \u06f1\u06f3\u06f8\u06f5)-\tSarmayeh Newspaper, number 257, (24 August 2006). \n* [http://www.sharghnewspaper.ir/830514/media.htm#s94047 /Journalist women under the shadow of constitutionalism]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.barnameh-budjeh.com/npview.asp?ID=1118573 Maryam Amid, Girls' Literacy Light]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amid, Maryam}}\n[[Category:People from Semnan, Iran]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:Iranian journalists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women journalists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Iranian women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Arepalli srinuvasa.Rao", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Venugopala Swamy temple yerrabalem-wikipedia)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maryam_Amid"}
{"title_page": "Vlade Divac", "text_new": "{{short description|Serbian basketball player and executive}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Vlade Divac\n| image = Vlade Divac 2016-mc.rs.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = Divac in 2016\n| team = Sacramento Kings\n| position = General manager\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| height_ft = 7\n| height_in = 1\n| weight_lbs = 255\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|02|03}}\n| birth_place = [[Prijepolje]], [[Socialist Republic of Serbia|SR Serbia]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]]\n| nationality = Serbian\n| high_school = \n| college = \n| draft_year = 1986\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 1\n| draft_team = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| career_number = 12, 21\n| career_position = [[Center (basketball)|Center]]\n| career_start = 1983\n| career_end = 2005\n| years1 = 1983-1984\n| team1 = [[KK Sloga|Sloga]] \n| years2 = 1984-1986\n| team2 = [[KK Partizan|Partizan]] \n| years3 = {{nbay|1986|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1991|end}}\n| team3 = [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n| years4 = {{nbay|1991|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1994|end}}\n| team4 = [[Charlotte Hornets]]\n| years5 = 1999\n| team5 = [[KK Crvena zvezda|Crvena zvezda]] \n| years6 = {{nbay|1994|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2000|end}}\n| team6 = [[Sacramento Kings]]\n| years7 = {{nbay|2000|full=y}}\n| team7 = Los Angeles Lakers\n| highlights = \n* [[NBA All-Star]] ({{nasg|2001}})\n* [[NBA All-Rookie First Team]] ({{nbay|1989|end}})\n* [[J. Walter Kennedy Citizenship Award]] ({{nbay|1999|end}})\n* No. 21 [[Sacramento Kings#Retired numbers|retired by Sacramento Kings]]\n* [[Mr. Europa|Mister Europa Player of the Year]] (1989)\n* [[FIBA's 50 Greatest Players (1991)|FIBA's 50 Greatest Players]] (1991)\n* [[50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors]] (2008)\n* [[Olympic Order]] (2016)\n| stats_league = NBA\n| stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value = 13,398 (11.8 ppg)\n| stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value = 9,326 (8.2 rpg)\n| stat3label = [[Block (basketball)|Blocks]]\n| stat3value = 1,631 (1.4 bpg)\n| bbr = divacvl01\n| FIBA_HOF_player=Vlade-Divac\n| HOF_player    = Vlade-Divac\n| medal_templates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[Basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{bk|YUG}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1988 Seoul]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1986 FIBA World Championship|1986 Spain]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1990 FIBA World Championship|1990 Argentina]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1987 EuroBasket|1987 Greece]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1989 EuroBasket|1989 Yugoslavia]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1991 EuroBasket|1991 Italy]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Summer Universiade|Universiade]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[Basketball at the 1987 Summer Universiade|1987 Zagreb]] |}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Under-19 World Championship|U19 World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1987 FIBA Under-19 World Championship|1987 Italy]]|[[Yugoslavia men's national under-19 basketball team|Under-19]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|European Championship for Cadets]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1985 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship|1985 Bulgaria]]|[[Yugoslavia men's national under-16 basketball team|Under-16]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flagicon|FR Yugoslavia}} [[Serbia and Montenegro national basketball team|FR Yugoslavia]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympic Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[Basketball at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996 Atlanta]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2002 FIBA World Championship|2002 USA]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[1995 EuroBasket|1995 Greece]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1999 EuroBasket|1999 France]]|}}\n}}\n'''Vlade Divac''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u0414\u0438\u0432\u0430\u0446}}, {{IPA-sh|\u028bl\u01ce\u02d0de d\u01d0\u02d0\u028bats|pron}}; born February 3, 1968) is a Serbian professional [[basketball]] executive and former player who is the vice president of basketball operations and general manager of the [[Sacramento Kings]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA).\n\nDivac spent most of his playing career in the NBA. At {{height|ft=7|in=1}},<ref>{{cite web |title=Vlade Divac Stats |url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/d/divacvl01.html |website=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=29 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref> he played [[center (basketball)|center]] and was known for his passing skills. He was among the first group of European basketball players to transfer to the NBA in the late 1980s and was named one of the [[50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroleague.net/item/24016 |title=Experts decide European Club Basketball's 50 greatest contributors \u2013 50 YEARS \u2013 Welcome to EUROLEAGUE BASKETBALL |publisher=Euroleague.net |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> He is one of seven players in NBA history to record 13,000 [[Point (basketball)|points]], 9,000 [[Rebound (basketball)|rebounds]], 3,000 [[Assist (basketball)|assists]], and 1,500 blocked shots, along with [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], [[Tim Duncan]], [[Shaquille O'Neal]], [[Kevin Garnett]], [[Pau Gasol]], and [[Hakeem Olajuwon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/lakers/news/divac_retires_051018.html |title=Vlade Divac Announces Retirement; Accepts Position With Lakers &#124|publisher=Nba.com |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref><ref group=n>The NBA did not record blocked shots before the 1973\u201374 season, so earlier players such as [[Bill Russell]] and [[Wilt Chamberlain]] probably had similar career achievements.</ref> Divac was also the first player born and trained outside the United States to play in over 1,000 games in the NBA. On August 20, 2010, he was inducted into the [[FIBA Hall of Fame]] in recognition of his play in international competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.halloffame.fiba.com/pages/eng/hof/news/p/newsid/42798/arti.html |title=FIBA announces 2010 Hall of Fame Class |publisher=[[FIBA]] |date=August 20, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019073536/http://www.halloffame.fiba.com/pages/eng/hof/news/p/newsid/42798/arti.html |archivedate=October 19, 2010 |df= }}</ref> He was elected to the [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]] in 2019.<ref name=\"hof\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.nba.com/article/2019/04/06/2019-naismith-basketball-hall-fame-announcement |title=Divac, Sikma, Moncrief headline Hall of Fame Class of 2019 |publisher=[[National Basketball Association]] |date=April 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAside from being noticed for his basketball abilities, Divac is also known as a humanitarian, helping children in his native country of Serbia and in Africa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/news/divac_youcantoo_070922.html |title=Divac Creates New Team With \"You Can Too\" Campaign |publisher=NBA.com |date=September 22, 2007 |accessdate=January 24, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011022055/http://www.nba.com/news/divac_youcantoo_070922.html |archive-date=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October 2008, he was appointed as government adviser in Serbia for humanitarian issues.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/news?slug=ap-divac-serbianadviser&prov=ap&type=lgns |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 17, 2008 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081020220122/http://sports.yahoo.com/nba/news?slug=ap-divac-serbianadviser&prov=ap&type=lgns |archivedate=October 20, 2008 }}</ref> In February 2009, he was elected President of the [[Serbian Olympic Committee]] for a 4-year term <ref name=\"blicokserb\">{{cite web |url=http://www.blic.rs/sport.php?id=80659 |title=Divac na \u010delu OKS naredne \u010detiri godine |language=Serbian |date=February 24, 2009 |publisher=Blic |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227115052/http://www.blic.rs/sport.php?id=80659 |archivedate=February 27, 2009 |df= }}</ref> and re-elected in November 2012.<ref name=oks>{{cite web|url=http://sport.blic.rs/Ostali-sportovi/223132/Divac-ponovo-izabran-za-predsednika-Olimpijskog-komiteta-Srbije |title=Vlade Divac ponovo izabran za predsednika Olimpijskog komiteta |language=Serbian |trans-title=Vlade Divac re-elected for the President of the Olympic Committee|publisher=Beta |date= November 7, 2012}}</ref> In 2013, Divac received an honor from the World Sports Humanitarian Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/kings/news/divac_hall_of_fame08.html |title=Kings News Full &#124; The Official Site Of The Sacramento Kings |publisher=Nba.com |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Club playing career==\nDivac began playing basketball in his home town [[Prijepolje]] for the team KK Elan. He began his professional career in Yugoslavia playing for [[KK Sloga|Sloga]] from [[Kraljevo]], and was immediately noted for scoring 27 points against [[KK Crvena zvezda|Crvena zvezda]].<ref name=\"vreme\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=512456 |title=Srbin broj jedan van Srbije |publisher=[[Vreme]] |date=September 20, 2007 |author=Slobodan Georgijev |language=Serbian}}</ref>\n\n===KK Partizan===\nIn the summer of 1986, Divac was the top star of the basketball transfer season, and he ended up signing with [[KK Partizan]] for [[Deutsche Mark|DM]]14,000.<ref name=\"vreme\" />\n\nIn the [[1986-87 Yugoslav First Basketball League|1986-87 Yugoslav First League season]], with players like Divac, [[Aleksandar \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107]], [[\u017darko Paspalj]], [[\u017deljko Obradovi\u0107]], and with [[head coach|coach]] [[Du\u0161ko Vujo\u0161evi\u0107]] at the helm, Partizan had a \"dream team\", which won the [[Yugoslavian First Federal Basketball League|Yugoslavian League]] title. In the subsequent [[1987-88 FIBA European Champions Cup|1987-88 FIBA European Champions Cup season]] (now called EuroLeague), the club failed to reach the top of the [[EuroLeague]], after having lost to [[Maccabi Tel Aviv B.C.|Maccabi Tel Aviv]] in [[1988 EuroLeague Final Four|the semifinal in Ghent]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stat.co.rs/partizan/eng/istorijat.php |title=Istorija: Novi \"Dream Team\" |publisher=[[KK Partizan|Partizan]] official website |accessdate=September 24, 2007}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> [[KK Split|Jugoplastika]], with [[Dino Ra\u0111a]] and [[Toni Kuko\u010d]], was a stronger team in the subsequent three years, reigning both in Yugoslavia and in Europe.\n\nDivac had an unusual style compared to most other [[center (basketball)|centers]] of his generation: despite his height, he possessed good mobility, had good control of the ball, and was a decent shooter. On occasion, he would also act as a [[point guard|play maker]]. His trademark moves included a mid-range shot at the top of the key and flip shots around the rim, while facing the complete opposite direction. His quirky moves complemented how he liked playing gags on the court: in the [[1989 EuroBasket]], he lifted teammate [[Zoran Radovi\u0107]] for a [[slam dunk]]. In just four professional seasons in Europe, he became the most sought-after big man on the continent, after [[Arvydas Sabonis]].<ref name=\"vreme\" />\n\n===Los Angeles Lakers===\nDrafted into the NBA in [[1989 NBA draft|1989]] by the [[Los Angeles Lakers]], Divac became one of the first European players to have an impact in the league. Under the mentorship of [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] and [[Magic Johnson]], he improved his play and adapted to the American style of basketball. Though he spoke no English, he quickly became popular among his teammates and the public for his charm and joviality. In the 1989&ndash;90 season, he was selected into the [[NBA All-Rookie Team]].<ref name=\"vreme\" />\n\nDivac earned a reputation for [[flop (basketball)|flopping]], or deceiving the officials into calling a foul on the other team by purposely falling to the floor upon contact with an opposing player.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/columnists/orl-nbainsider2807jan28,0,6686181.column?track=rss |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120907202921/http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/columnists/orl-nbainsider2807jan28,0,6686181.column?track=rss |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 7, 2012 |title=Shutting down acting school? |author=Tim Povtak |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=January 28, 2007 |accessdate=April 29, 2007 }}</ref> Veteran NBA forward [[P. J. Brown]] claimed that Divac might have been the best of all time at flopping.<ref>[http://www.azcentral.com/sports/suns/articles/0318nbaflop0318.html Flopping keeps cropping up], by Doug Haller, ''The Arizona Republic'', published March 18, 2007, retrieved April 29, 2007</ref> Divac freely admitted doing so, adding that he usually did it when he felt like the officials had missed some calls and owed him.<ref>[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/BEST+ACTOR:+DIVAC+IN+%60FLOP+WARS+II'-a086219289 BEST ACTOR: DIVAC IN `FLOP WARS II'], by Kevin Modesti, Los Angeles ''Daily News'', published May 22, 2002</ref> However, when the NBA instituted anti-flopping penalties in 2012, Divac expressed his support for such rules, stating that he felt players after him were \"overdo[ing] it\" with respect to flopping.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/kings/2015/03/10/vlade-divac-sacramento-front-office-vivek-ranadive-flopping-lakers-kobe-bryant/24666243/|title=Even Vlade Divac thinks flopping has gotten out of hand|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Ian Thomsen, a ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' columnist, grouped Divac with fellow international players [[Anderson Varej\u00e3o]] and [[Manu Gin\u00f3bili]] as the players who \"made [flopping] famous\", exaggerating contact on the court in a manner analogous to [[diving (football)|diving]] in [[FIFA]] games.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/writers/ian_thomsen/09/28/nba-flopping-david-stern/ | title= NBA's new flopping policy the best response to a difficult problem | date= September 28, 2012 | first= Ian |last= Thomsen |work= [[Sports Illustrated]] | publisher= cnn.com| accessdate=September 28, 2012| quote= The ugly trend of faking physical contact began in soccer, a sport in which gamesmanship has given way to players writhing in false agony around the world. Soccer has been unable to fix its problem, but now the NBA will have an opportunity to deter players from trying to simulate violent contact in ways made famous by Vlade Divac, Manu Ginobili and Anderson Varejao.}}</ref>\n\n===Charlotte Hornets===\nOn July 01, 1996, Divac was traded to the [[Charlotte Hornets]] for the draft rights to [[Kobe Bryant]] and played two seasons there until signing with the Sacramento Kings in July 1998.\n\n===Two games with KK Crvena zvezda===\nDuring the [[1998-99 NBA lockout]], in January 1999, Divac played 2 games for Partizan's [[Eternal derby (Serbia)|eternal rival]] [[KK Crvena Zvezda]], in the [[1998\u201399 FIBA EuroLeague|1998-99 EuroLeague season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.compID_,Uz02qBnJiADOq5VntEf53.roundID_2570.season_1999.teamID_1490.playerID_2626.html |title=profile |publisher=Fibaeurope.com |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nHis debut for the ''crveno-beli'' took place mid-season, on [[Orthodox Christmas]], versus a heavily favoured [[BC \u017dalgiris|\u017dalgiris]] side led by [[Tyus Edney]], [[Mindaugas \u017dukauskas]], [[Saulius \u0160tombergas]], and [[George Zidek|Ji\u0159\u00ed Z\u00eddek Jr.]]. Supported by a raucous home crowd and energized by Divac's arrival, as well as his 16 points and 8 rebounds, Crvena zvezda pulled off a 77-69 memorable upset win.<ref name=\"mondo-feb-2015\">{{cite news|url=http://mondo.rs/a767526/Sport/Kosarka/Zvezda-Zalgiris-secanje-na-debi-Vlade-Divca.html|title=Pro\u0161li put protiv \u017dalgirisa za Zvezdu je igrao...|agency=mondo.rs|date=February 4, 2015|accessdate=February 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDivac's brief stint with Crvena zvezda, for which he reportedly got paid US$250,000 per game,<ref name=\"mondo-feb-2015\"/> immediately became a sore point with KK Partizan fans, who unfurled a banner calling him a traitor, at their club's next game.<ref name=\"mondo-feb-2015\"/>\n\nThe issue of playing for the hated cross-town rival reignited several years later, when Divac returned to KK Partizan as club president. At the time, he stated his decision to play for Crvena zvezda was \"a mistake\".<ref name=\"mondo-feb-2015\"/>\n\n===Sacramento Kings===\nHe then signed as a [[free agent]] with the [[Sacramento Kings]] where he played for six seasons alongside fellow countryman [[Peja Stojakovi\u0107]]. Teamed with Stojakovi\u0107, [[Hedo T\u00fcrko\u011flu]], [[Chris Webber]] and [[Mike Bibby]]; Divac revitalized the [[Sacramento Kings]] franchise. The Kings rose in the NBA ranks, becoming a perennial playoff contender and eventually a championship contender, leading the league in wins in [[2001-02 NBA season|2001-02]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/standings?season=2002&group=league&seasontype=2&standType=standings |title=NBA Standings \u2013 2001-2002 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> The Kings, however, could not get past the [[Los Angeles Lakers]], who beat them in a  [[2002 NBA Playoffs#Conference Finals|7-game series in 2002.]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/basketball/ex-referee-tim-donaghy-blows-whistle-nba-dirty-secrets-article-1.293192|title=Ex-referee Tim Donaghy blows whistle on NBA dirty secrets|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Return to the Lakers===\nAfter the [[2003-04 NBA season]], Divac became a [[free agent]]. He signed a deal to return to the Lakers, part of [[Mitch Kupchak]]'s plan to overhaul Laker basketball. The Lakers, following a defeat in the NBA Finals, had traded away or released most of their players, including [[Shaquille O'Neal]], [[Gary Payton]], [[Karl Malone]], [[Derek Fisher]], and more; Divac was supposed to help fill that void.\n\nHowever, Divac suffered back problems and could not play most of the season, and even when he returned, could only play about nine minutes per game, averaging 2.3 points per game and 2.1 rebounds per game in 15 games, he played 8 games early in the season and 7 more in the final month of the season.\n\nOn July 14, 2005, 37-year-old Divac announced his retirement, ending his 16-year NBA and 22-year professional basketball career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/lakers/news/divac_retires_051018.html|title=Vlade Divac Announces Retirement; Accepts Position With Lakers - THE OFFICIAL SITE OF THE LOS ANGELES LAKERS|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> Divac accepted a position with the Lakers as a European liaison to help with scouting overseas.\n\n===Retirement===\nThe Kings retired his No. 21 jersey in a ceremony on March 31, 2009.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090401/ap_on_sp_bk_ne/bkn_kings_divac_honored;_ylt=An5HUchghgZmP09wgS_FjaILMxIF Kings retire Divac's No. 21 Jersey]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Yahoo! Sports, March 31, 2009</ref>  Over his 16 years in the NBA, Divac earned over $93 million in salary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/d/divacvl01.html |title=Vlade Divac NBA & ABA Stats |publisher=Basketball-Reference.com |date= |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> In September 2009, he played for the \"NBA Generations\" team in the 2009 NBA Asia Challenge, a series of exhibitions against [[Korean Basketball League]] and [[Philippine Basketball Association]] players.<ref>{{cite web|title=NBA Asia Challenge 2009|url=http://www.nba.com/asiachallenge2009/|website=NBA.com|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\n[[File:Vlade Divac & Drazen Petrovic in Argentina 1990.jpg|thumb|right|170px|Divac with [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]] in the [[1990 FIBA World Championship]] held in Argentina.]]\n\nIn summer 1986, at 18, right after signing for KK Partizan, Divac debuted for the senior [[Yugoslavia national basketball team]] at the [[1986 FIBA World Championship]] in Madrid, on invitation by the head coach [[Kre\u0161imir \u0106osi\u0107]]. However, the excellent rookie's performance was spoiled by the event in the semi-finals against the [[Soviet Union national basketball team|Soviet Union]]. Forty-five seconds before the end, Yugoslavia had a comfortable lead of 9 points, but the Soviets scored two three-pointers within a few seconds and cut the difference to 3 points. Yugoslavia tried to hold the ball for the remaining time, opting to continue the play with throw-ins instead of free throws following fouls, but with only 14 seconds left, Divac committed a [[double dribble]], the Soviets were awarded the ball, and tied the score with another three-pointer. In the overtime, the Soviets easily prevailed against the shocked Yugoslavs, who had to be content with the bronze.<ref name=\"vreme\" />\n\nThe next year, Divac participated in the team that took the gold at the [[1987 FIBA Under-19 World Cup|1987 FIBA Junior World Championship]] (which was later split into separate [[FIBA Under-19 World Championship|under-19]] and [[FIBA Under-21 World Championship|under-21]] events) in [[Bormio]], Italy. That event launched the young generation of Yugoslavian basketball players, also featuring stars like Ra\u0111a and Kuko\u010d, regarded as likely the best in history. Before the [[breakup of Yugoslavia]], they would also take the titles at [[EuroBasket 1989]] and the [[1990 FIBA World Championship]] in [[Argentina]],<ref name=\"vreme\" /> where they were led by [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]],<ref name=\"fiba1989\">{{cite web |url=http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.teamID_390.compID_qMRZdYCZI6EoANOrUf9le2.season_1989.roundID_938.html |title=Eurobasket 1989 |publisher=[[FIBA]]}}</ref> as well as the [[EuroBasket 1991]] title, with [[Aleksandar \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107]] at [[point guard]].<ref name=\"fiba1991\">{{cite web |\nurl=http://www.fibaeurope.com/cid_KNce8jInH7Qj1EsyH5rjn2.teamID_390.compID_qMRZdYCZI6EoANOrUf9le2.season_1991.roundID_2263.html |title=Eurobasket 1991 |publisher=[[FIBA]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Yugoslavia 1990 basketball.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Divac (fourth from right, at centre) with the [[Yugoslavia national basketball team|Yugoslavia team]] that won the [[EuroBasket 1989]].]]\nWhen Yugoslavia won the gold in the [[1990 FIBA World Championship]], fans rushed onto the court. One of them was holding a [[Croatia]]n flag, one of the six republics that made up Yugoslavia. Divac claims that he told the man that he should not be waving that flag, since this was a win for Yugoslavia. Divac claims the man made a derogatory remark about the Yugoslav flag, at which point Divac took his flag from him. This happened during a very tense time where nationalistic pride was threatening to tear Yugoslavia apart and ignite a war. The taking of the flag made Divac a hero to Serbs, and a villain to Croatians. Divac has stated that he did not mean it as an act against Croatia and he would have taken away a Serbian flag if a Serb fan had done the same.<ref name=once>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/once-brothers,46215/| title=Once Brothers |publisher=A. V. club |author=Scott Tobias |date=October 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/12/entertainment/la-et-vlade-divac-20101012 |title=Television review: Vlade Divac searches for closure in ESPN's 'Once Brothers' |publisher=LA Times |author=John Scheibe |date=December 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThis action, along with the [[Yugoslav Wars]], alienated Divac from many of his former Croatian friends, particularly [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], whom he considered his best friend.<ref name=once/> When [[Serbia and Montenegro national basketball team|FR Yugoslavia]] won the gold medal at the [[EuroBasket 1995]], and [[Croatia national basketball team|Croatia]] won bronze, Croatia, still at [[War in Croatia|war with Serbs from Croatia]], walked off the podium during the medal ceremony. The teams had not faced each other in the tournament.\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n[[File:Vlade Divac by Djuradj Vujcic.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Divac is one of seven players in NBA history to record 13,000 points, 9,000 rebounds, 3,000 assists, and 1,500 blocked shots.]]\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1989}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1989\u201390 Los Angeles Lakers season|LA Lakers]]\n| '''82''' || 5 || 19.6 || .499 || .000 || .708 || 6.2 || 0.9 || 1.0 || 1.4 || 8.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1990|trunc=y}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Los Angeles Lakers|LA Lakers]]\n| '''82''' || '''81''' || 28.2 || '''.565''' || '''.357''' || .703 || 8.1 || 1.1 || 1.3 || 1.5 || 11.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1991}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Los Angeles Lakers|LA Lakers]]\n| 36 || 18 || 27.2 || .495 || .263 || .768 || 6.9 || 1.7 || 1.5 || 1.0 || 11.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1992}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Los Angeles Lakers|LA Lakers]]\n| '''82''' || 69 || 30.8 || .485 || .280 || .689 || 8.9 || 2.8 || '''1.6''' || 1.7 || 12.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1993}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Los Angeles Lakers|LA Lakers]]\n| 79 || 73 || 34.0 || .506 || .191 || .686 || '''10.8''' || 3.9 || 1.2 || 1.4 || 14.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1994}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Los Angeles Lakers|LA Lakers]]\n| 80 || 80 || 35.1 || .507 || .185 || '''.777''' || 10.4|| 4.1 || 1.4