"| [[Los Angeles Lakers|LA Lakers]]\n| 4 || 4 || 28.8 || .429 || .200 || .625 || 7.5 || 2.0 || 0.0 || 1.3 || 9.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1997 NBA Playoffs|1997]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Charlotte Hornets|Charlotte]]\n| 3 || 3 || 38.7 || .457 || .000 || .800 || 8.7 || 3.3 || 1.0 || 2.0 || '''18.0'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1998 NBA Playoffs|1998]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Charlotte Hornets|Charlotte]]\n| 9 || 9 || 38.5 || .483 || .000 || .606 || '''10.9''' || 3.4 || 0.8 || 1.6 || 11.6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1999 NBA Playoffs|1999]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Sacramento Kings|Sacramento]]\n| 5 || 5 || '''39.6''' || .446 || .200 || .833 || 10.0 || 4.6 || '''1.6''' || 0.8 || 16.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2000 NBA Playoffs|2000]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Sacramento Kings|Sacramento]]\n| 5 || 5 || 32.0 || .357 || .000 || .696 || 7.2 || 2.8 || 1.4 || 0.8 || 11.2\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2001 NBA Playoffs|2001]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Sacramento Kings|Sacramento]]\n| 8 || 8 || 28.1 || .350 || .333 || .763 || 8.4 || 2.4 || 1.0 || 1.5 || 10.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2002 NBA Playoffs|2002]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Sacramento Kings|Sacramento]]\n| 16 || 16 || 33.4 || .464 || .268 || .755 || 9.3 || 1.7 || 1.1 || 1.3 || 13.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2003 NBA Playoffs|2003]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Sacramento Kings|Sacramento]]\n| 12 || 12 || 26.4 || .560 || .000 || .673 || 5.8 || 2.3 || 0.7 || 0.9 || 11.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2004 NBA Playoffs|2004]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[Sacramento Kings|Sacramento]]\n| 12 || 12 || 19.6 || .437 || .000 || .739 || 4.9 || 1.8 || 0.3 || 0.4 || 6.6\n|-class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| '''Career'''\n| 121 || 113 || 30.8 || .480 || .241 || .731 || 7.5 || 2.4 || 1.0 || 1.4 || 12.1\n{{s-end}}\n\n==Major career achievements==\n\n===KK Partizan===\n* [[Yugoslav Basketball League|Yugoslav League]] Champion: ([[1986\u201387 Yugoslav First Basketball League|1987]])\n* [[1988 EuroLeague Final Four]]: 3rd Place\n* [[Yugoslav Basketball Cup|Yugoslav Cup]] Winner: (1989)\n* [[FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup|Kora\u0107 Cup]] Winner: ([[1988\u201389 FIBA Kora\u0107 Cup|1989]])\n\n===Yugoslavia national team===\n* Earned gold medal with [[Yugoslavia men's national under-16 basketball team|Yugoslavia's under-18 nationals]] at the [[1985 FIBA Europe Under-16 Championship]] in [[Rousse]], [[Bulgaria]]\n* Earned gold medal with [[Yugoslavia men's national under-18 basketball team|Yugoslavia's under-21 nationals]] at the [[1986 FIBA Europe Under-18 Championship]] in [[Gmunden]], Austria\n* Earned gold medal with [[Yugoslavia men's national under-19 basketball team|Yugoslavia's under-21 nationals]] at the [[1987 FIBA Under-19 World Cup]] in [[Bormio]], Italy, defeating the U.S. team twice in that tournament\n* Earned silver medals in [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1988 Summer Olympic Games]] (for [[Yugoslavian national basketball team|SFR Yugoslavia]]) and [[Basketball at the 1996 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|1996 Summer Olympic Games]] (for [[FR Yugoslavia national basketball team|FR Yugoslavia]])\n* Earned gold medals with [[Yugoslavian national basketball team|SFRY]] at the [[1990 FIBA World Championship]] ([[Argentina]]) and with [[FR Yugoslavia national basketball team|FRY]] at the [[2002 FIBA World Championship]] (U.S.)\n* Earned gold medals at [[EuroBasket]] in [[EuroBasket 1989|Zagreb 1989]], and [[EuroBasket 1991|Rome 1991]] (with [[Yugoslavian national basketball team|SFRY]]), and in [[EuroBasket 1995|Athens 1995]] (with [[FR Yugoslavia national basketball team|FRY]])\n\n===NBA===\n* Named to the 1989\u201390 NBA All-Rookie First Team after averaging 8.5 ppg and 6.2 rpg for the Lakers\n* Appeared in the 1991 NBA Finals against the Chicago Bulls and averaged 12.1 ppg, 7.5 rpg and 2.4 apg in 121 career NBA Playoff games\n* Ranks 4th in Lakers franchise history with 830 blocked shots\n* Ranked 2nd on the Kings in scoring (14.3 ppg), rebounds (10.0 rpg, 10th in the NBA), assists (4.3 apg) and blocked shots (1.02 bpg) in 1998\u201399\n* Named NBA All-Star, 2001\n* One of only five basketball players born and trained in Europe to [[List of National Basketball Association players with 1000 games played|play at least 1,000 NBA games]] (1,134; along with [[Dirk Nowitzki]], [[Tony Parker]], [[Pau Gasol]], [[Boris Diaw]])\n* One of only four basketball players born and trained in Europe ([[Peja Stojakovi\u0107]], [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]] and [[Zydrunas Ilgauskas]] are the others) to have his number retired by an NBA team\n\n==Administrative career==\nThrough the twilight of his playing career and afterwards, Divac focused on three fields: humanitarian work, sport management, and investment.\n\n===KK Partizan president===\nIn late 2000, following the [[overthrow of Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]] whose policies Divac had been openly critical of throughout mid-to-late 1990s,<ref name=\"si-may1999-Rick Reilly\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1999/05/24/261148/vlade-divacs-private-war |title=Vlade Divac's Private War |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=May 24, 1999 |author=Rick Reilly|author-link=Rick Reilly }}</ref> Divac and former teammate [[Predrag Danilovi\u0107]] took over their former club [[KK Partizan]]. They did so on initiative by [[Ivica Da\u010di\u0107]], the club's outgoing president and, more importantly, a suddenly marginalized politician who, due to his association with Milo\u0161evi\u0107, was forced to leave his post at the club. Seeing that various state-owned companies and community property were being taken over in a dubious manner during the power vacuum that resulted from r\u00e9gime change, Da\u010di\u0107 saw it prudent to bring the club's two former greats as a safeguard against the same happening to KK Partizan. Divac became the club's president while Danilovi\u0107 took the vice-president role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Politika/61059/Divac-savetuje-Dacica |title=Divac savetuje Da\u010di\u0107a |work=[[Blic]] |date=October 16, 2008 |author=\u017d. Jevti\u0107}}</ref>\n\nFreshly retired from playing, Danilovi\u0107 was actually running the club's day-to-day operations since Divac was still very actively involved with the [[Sacramento Kings]] at the time. The head coach they inherited, [[Darko Russo]], finished out the 2000\u201301 season before they decided in summer 2001 to bring back their mentor [[Du\u0161ko Vujo\u0161evi\u0107]] to be the new head coach.\n\nThough the duo never stated so outright, their additional motivation in getting involved with KK Partizan again was perceived to be gaining the upper hand on the club's eventual privatisation process once the new Law on Sports gets passed in the [[National Assembly of Serbia|Serbian parliament]]. Since the exact ownership structure of a publicly owned KK Partizan wasn't and still isn't really clear, potential investors decided to stay away, at least until the law appears. Divac and Danilovi\u0107 appeared pretty much out of nowhere in this regard but enjoyed plenty of fan and public support because most preferred to see their beloved club owned and operated by its former stars rather than a faceless corporation or a group of politicians, managers or businessmen close to the ruling coalition. However, after a few years the duo ran out of patience and pulled out of the venture in late 2004 because it became too much of a financial burden with no end-goal in sight. While he stopped performing any official functions at the club, Divac continued to be involved with it in a lesser capacity for a few years afterwards.\n\n===LA Lakers scout===\nIn October 2005, right after ending his playing career with the [[Los Angeles Lakers]], Divac got hired as the Lakers' European scout, reporting directly to the team's general manager [[Mitch Kupchak]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/news/story?id=2196445|title=Divac to serve as scout, liaison in Europe|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|agency=[[ESPN.com]]|date=October 19, 2005|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> He left the position in 2006.\n\n===Real Madrid Baloncesto club management===\nIn June 2006, through his friendship with [[Predrag Mijatovi\u0107]], Divac linked up with [[Ram\u00f3n Calder\u00f3n]] as part of the lawyer's candidate bid for the presidency of [[Real Madrid]] [[polideportivo]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/deportes/2006/06/05/actualidad/1149492115_850215.html|title=Calder\u00f3n presenta su proyecto para el Real Madrid con Mijatovic como director deportivo|agency=''[[El Pa\u00eds]]''|date=June 5, 2006|accessdate=April 16, 2018}}</ref> When Calder\u00f3n closely won the club elections on July 2, 2006, Divac was announced as the head of operations at [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]] basketball club though the scope of his job description soon got reduced to consulting duties as president Calder\u00f3n's adviser for basketball and club's international coordinator.<ref name=\"elmundo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2008/04/02/baloncesto/1207128247.html|title=El incre\u00edble caso de Vlade Divac|agency=''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]''|date=April 4, 2008|accessdate=July 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://elpais.com/deportes/2006/09/22/actualidad/1158909714_850215.html|title=Divac llega al Real Madrid como \"asesor\" y con el \"gran reto de traer la NBA a Europa\"|agency=''[[El Pa\u00eds]]''|date=September 22, 2006|accessdate=July 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Divac's role in the club's day-to-day operations turned out to be largely symbolic, and he even admitted as much in a March 2007 interview for Croatian weekly ''[[Globus (weekly)|Globus]]'': \"I literally do nothing and I only serve as part of the ''royal club'''s image. I only accepted the job because of Mijatovi\u0107, who is currently the football director at Real\".<ref name=\"mondo\">{{cite web |url=http://mondo.rs/a52680/Sport/Kosarka/Divac-Kandidovacu-se-za-predsednika-Srbije.html |title=Divac: Kandidova\u0107u se za predsednika Srbije |publisher=MONDO web portal |language=Serbian |date=March 8, 2007 }}</ref> By the end of 2007, following a financial settlement between the two parties, Divac moved on from the post for which he had been reportedly receiving an annual compensation of [[\u20ac]]300,000.<ref name=\"elmundo\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/futbol/vlade-divac-cobro-300000-euros-por-no-hacer-nada-5822564|title=Vlade Divac cobr\u00f3 300.000 euros por no hacer nada|agency=Sport.es|date=July 14, 2008|accessdate=July 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Serbian Deputy Prime Minister's adviser===\nIn October 2008, Divac's [[political consulting|political advisory]] engagement within the [[Cabinet of Mirko Cvetkovi\u0107|Serbian government]] as the sports, [[diaspora]], and humanitarian advisor to the [[Deputy Prime Minister of Serbia|Deputy Prime Minister]] and [[Ministry of Internal Affairs (Serbia)|Internal Affairs Minister]] [[Ivica Da\u010di\u0107]], got announced.<ref>{{cite news|last=J.|first=\u017d.|url=https://www.blic.rs/vesti/politika/divac-dobija-kancelariju-u-vladi/gvxrmfk|title=Divac dobija kancelariju u Vladi|agency=''[[Blic]]''|date=October 17, 2008|accessdate=April 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/basketball/2008/10/16/vlade_divac_appointed_adviser_to_serbia.html|title=Vlade Divac appointed adviser to Serbia|agency=''[[Toronto Star]]''|date=October 16, 2008|accessdate=April 16, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Carr|first=Janis|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2008/10/16/divac-playing-new-role/|title=Divac playing new role|agency=''[[Orange County Register]]''|date=October 16, 2008|accessdate=April 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Olympic Committee of Serbia president===\nDivac was proposed in 2000 as Yugoslavia's candidate for the Sport Commission of the International Olympic Committee in spring 2000. This candidature was withdrawn under pressure from Milo\u0161evi\u0107 regime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vreme.com/arhiva_html/490/03.html|title=Apel \"Vremena\" H.A. Samaranu|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> In February 2009, Divac ran for presidency of the [[Olympic Committee of Serbia]] against incumbent president [[Ivan \u0106urkovi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.blic.rs/sports.php?id=3867 |title=Curkovic backs Divac bid |publisher=[[Blic]] |date=February 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215120515/http://www.blic.rs/sports.php?id=3867 |archivedate=February 15, 2009 |df= }}</ref> He won the race after \u0106urkovi\u0107 withdrew just before the scheduled voting.<ref name=\"blicokserb\" /> In November 2012, he was re-elected as the sole candidate; the end of his second mandate coincides with the [[2016 Summer Olympics]] in Rio de Janeiro.<ref name=oks/>\n\nIn December 2014, [[Kosovo]] was accepted as a full member of the [[International Olympic Committee]]. Divac and the Serbian Olympic Committee have been criticised, chiefly by the [[Democratic Party of Serbia]], for failing to take any effort to prevent that.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtv.rs/sr_lat/politika/dss-da-li-je-divac-pokusao-da-spreci-ulazak-kosova-u-mok_547452.html |title=DSS: Da li je Divac poku\u0161ao da spre\u010di ulazak Kosova u MOK |publisher=Radio Television of Vojvodina |date=December 14, 2014 |language=Serbian}}</ref> Divac stated that he is not happy with the decision of the IOC, but could not have prevented it as it had already been made, and said he would accept it \"in the interest of the athletes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2014/12/09/olympics-kosovo-idINKBN0JN10S20141209 |title=Kosovo earns Olympic recognition, Serbia furious |agency=Reuters |date=December 10, 2014 |author=Karolos Grohmann}}</ref>\n\nOn May 9, 2017, he was succeeded by Serbian former basketball coach [[Bo\u017eidar Maljkovi\u0107]] on position of the president of [[Olympic Committee of Serbia]].<ref>[http://sport.blic.rs/ostali-sportovi/bozidar-maljkovic-novi-predsednik-olimpijskog-komiteta-srbije/ws3p3fb Bo\u017eidar Maljkovi\u0107 novi predsednik Olimpijskog komiteta Srbije!]</ref>\n\n===Sacramento Kings front office===\n====Initial advisory role====\nIn early March 2015, Divac was hired by the [[Sacramento Kings]] as their vice president of basketball and franchise operations.<ref name=\"divac-kings-march2015\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/kings/2015/03/03/vlade-divac-sacramento-vice-president-basketball-franchise-operations-george-karl/24326819/ |title=Kings hire Vlade Divac as vice president, adviser |work=USA Today Sports |date=March 3, 2015 |author=Adi Joseph}}</ref> Brought into the organization by the principal owner [[Vivek Ranadiv\u00e9]] towards the end of a turbulent [[2014\u201315 Sacramento Kings season|season]], Divac's arrival came in the wake of head coach [[Michael Malone (basketball)|Mike Malone]]'s firing and the eventual hiring of [[George Karl]]. Working alongside the team's general manager [[Pete D'Alessandro]], Divac's initial duties with the Kings were reported to be advising the front office and coaches as well as assisting with branding and fan outreach.<ref name=\"divac-kings-march2015\"/> However, such broadly defined job responsibilities immediately led to press speculation about Divac's role within the organization that in addition to general manager D'Alessandro also featured assistant GM [[Mike Bratz]], special assistant to the GM [[Mitch Richmond]], director of player personnel and analytics [[Dean Oliver (statistician)|Dean Oliver]], adviser to the chairman [[Chris Mullin (basketball)|Chris Mullin]], as well as a head coach, Karl, who has always wanted to be involved in personnel issues.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ziller|first=Tom|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2015/3/20/8263149/vivek-ranadive-kings-front-office-warriors-vlade-divac|title=The Kings are trying hard to be the Warriors and failing miserably|agency=[[SB Nation]]|date=March 20, 2015|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref> Within a month of Divac's hiring, [[ESPN]]'s [[Marc Stein (reporter)|Marc Stein]] reported that \"despite the Kings not yet announcing their new power structure, Divac is indeed already regarded as the team's top basketball official by owner Ranadiv\u00e9\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Marc|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/12644960/vlade-divac-emerges-sacramento-kings-lead-voice|title=Vlade Divac emerges as Kings' lead voice|agency=[[ESPN.com]]|date=April 8, 2015|accessdate=April 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn June 10, 2015, two weeks before the NBA draft, general manager D'Alessandro left the Kings by accepting a front-office position with the Denver Nuggets amid reports he did so due to being stripped of his decision-making power after Ranadiv\u00e9 hired Divac.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Jason|url=http://www.sacbee.com/sports/nba/sacramento-kings/kings-blog/article23669575.html|title=Kings general manager Pete D\u2019Alessandro takes job with Nuggets|agency=''[[Sacramento Bee]]''|date=June 10, 2015|accessdate=April 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ziller|first=Tom|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2015/6/11/8764711/sacramento-kings-front-office-vlade-divac-vivek-ranadive|title=The Kings front office is even messier than it appears|agency=[[SB Nation]]|date=June 11, 2015|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOnly days before the draft, animosity between head coach Karl and the team's star center [[DeMarcus Cousins]] reignited, as Karl reportedly lobbied Divac, as well as multiple players on the Kings' roster, in order to make the case to owner Ranadive that Cousins needs to be traded.<ref>{{cite news|last=[[Adrian Wojnarowski|Wojnarowski]]|first=[[Adrian Wojnarowski|Adrian]]|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/sources--george-karl-pushing-for-kings-to-trade-demarcus-cousins-051748948.html|title=Sources: George Karl pushing for Kings to trade DeMarcus Cousins|agency=[[Yahoo Sports]]|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> As a result, against the backdrop of Cousins calling Karl a \"snake\" on Twitter,<ref>{{cite news|last=Zller|first=Tom|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2015/6/23/8830539/george-karl-snake-demarcus-cousins-history|title=A brief history of NBA stars calling George Karl a snake|agency=[[SB Nation]]|date=June 23, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> Divac reportedly discussed multiple Cousins trade scenarios with various teams, but ultimately no deal got made.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wojnarowski|first=Adrian|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/sources--kings-talking-to-lakers-about-demarcus-cousins-trade--fielding-offers-from-other-teams-030157845.html|title=Sources: Kings talking to Lakers about DeMarcus Cousins trade, fielding offers from other teams|agency=[[Yahoo Sports]]|date=June 24, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> At the [[2015 NBA draft]], with the 6th pick, the Kings selected 21-year-old center [[Willie Cauley-Stein]] out of [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]]. Less than a week following the draft, with the dissolution of the Karl\u2014Cousins relationship on public display, the Kings' ultimately unsuccessful attempt at landing University of Kentucky head coach [[John Calipari]] to replace Karl got reported.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wojnarowski|first=Adrian|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/sources--kings--john-calipari--kentucky-195614697.html|title=Sources: Kings probing John Calipari about coaching, front-office jobs|agency=[[Yahoo Sports]]|date=June 30, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThen in early July 2015, in an effort of clearing [[NBA salary cap|salary cap]] space in order to immediately go after [[free agent]]s, they agreed a trade with the Philadelphia 76ers, sending [[Nik Stauskas]], [[Carl Landry]], [[Jason Thompson (basketball)|Jason Thompson]] along with the Kings' future first round draft pick to the Sixers as well as the rights to swap first round picks in 2016 and 2017 while receiving the rights to Sixers oversees players [[Art\u016bras Gudaitis]] and [[Luka Mitrovi\u0107]] in return.<ref>{{cite news|last=Feldman|first=Dan|url=https://nba.nbcsports.com/2015/07/01/76ers-get-nik-stauskas-in-salary-dump-trade-with-kings/|title=76ers get Nik Stauskas, first-rounder in salary-dump trade with Kings|agency=[[NBC Sports]]|date=July 1, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref> Two days later, they agreed the acquisitions of two free agents: twenty-nine-year-old [[Marco Belinelli]] on a three-year US$19 million contract and twenty-nine-year-old point guard [[Rajon Rondo]] for one year for US$10 million.<ref>{{cite news|last=Herbert|first=James|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/rajon-rondo-kings-agree-to-1-year-10-million-deal/|title=Rajon Rondo, Kings agree to 1-year, $10 million deal\n|agency=[[CBSSports.com]]|date=July 3, 2015|accessdate=July 8, 2018}}</ref> This was followed by signing twenty-six-year-old center [[Kosta Koufos]] for four years and US$33 million with his role envisioned as backup for Cousins.<ref>{{cite news|last=Golliver|first=Ben|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2015/07/07/kosta-koufos-sacramento-kings-free-agency-grades-demarcus-cousins|title=Grade the deal: Kings cap strange summer by signing Kosta Koufos|agency=[[SI.com]]|date=July 7, 2015|accessdate=July 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWith the free agent signings done, Divac turned his attention to attempting to mend the relations between the team's head coach Karl and its star center Cousins ahead of the 2015-16 season, admitting publicly on July 9, 2015 on [[CBS Sports Radio]]'s ''[[The Jim Rome Show]]'' that the relationship between the two \"isn't pretty right now\".<ref>{{cite news|author=ESPN.com news services|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/13229088/vlade-divac-sacramento-kings-george-karl-demarcus-cousins-union-not-pretty-right-now|title=Vlade Divac working to make Karl-Cousins relationship better|agency=[[ESPN.com]]|date=July 9, 2015|accessdate=July 8, 2018}}</ref> A few days later, on July 13, 2015, during a [[2015 NBA Summer League]] game in [[Las Vegas]], the two shared an awkward on-camera handshake as Karl approached and Cousins reluctantly shook the coach's hand before turning away.<ref>{{cite news|author=ESPN.com news services|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Sports/kings-coach-george-karl-demarcus-cousins-share-awkward/story?id=32439225|title=Kings coach George Karl, DeMarcus Cousins share awkward handshake|agency=[[Abcnews.go.com]]|date=July 14, 2015|accessdate=July 8, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"voisin-april-2016\">{{cite news|last=Voisin|first=Ailene|url=https://www.sacbee.com/sports/spt-columns-blogs/ailene-voisin/article74937347.html|title=George Karl reflective after firing by Kings|agency=''[[Sacramento Bee]]''|date=April 30, 2016|accessdate=July 8, 2018}}</ref> Later that week, Divac summoned Cousins and Karl to a private counseling session.<ref name=\"voisin-april-2016\"/>\n\n====Promotion to general manager====\nDivac was promoted to the Kings' vice president of basketball operations and general manager on August 31, 2015.<ref name=\"divac-gm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/kings/new/kings-announce-basketball-operations-update|title=Kings Announce Basketball Operations Update|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc.|date=August 31, 2015|accessdate=August 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAmid a tense<ref>{{cite news|author=ESPN.com news services|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/16185384/rajon-rondo-tension-filled-sacramento-kings-never-jelled-team|title=Rajon Rondo details Kings' woes, sends thoughts to Orlando|agency=[[ESPN.com]]|date=June 14, 2016|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> and incident-filled<ref>{{cite news|author=''Slam'' staff|url=https://www.slamonline.com/uncategorized/demarcus-cousins-reportedly-cursed-out-george-karl-monday-night/|title=DeMarcus Cousins Reportedly Cursed Out George Karl Monday Night|agency=''[[Slam (magazine)|Slam]]''|date=November 11, 2015|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> [[2015\u201316 Sacramento Kings season|season]] that saw the team briefly reach the final [[2016 NBA Playoffs|playoff]] spot in the [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] before unravelling with extended losing streaks in late January and early February 2016, the organization reportedly made a decision to fire their head coach George Karl during the upcoming [[2016 NBA All-Star Game|All-Star break]], a move pushed for by Divac.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Marc|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/14744059/sacramento-kings-planning-fire-coach-george-karl-coming-days|title=Sources: Kings planning to fire coach George Karl in coming days|agency=[[ESPN.com]]|date=February 9, 2016|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> However, in a quick about-face, Karl got retained after meeting with Divac and reportedly pledging to make changes to address concerns within the organization about his defensive schemes and practice policies.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Marc|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/14747006/sacramento-kings-retain-george-karl-coach|title=Kings to retain George Karl after meeting with Vlade Divac|agency=[[ESPN.com]]|date=February 9, 2016|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> It was later reported that the move to fire Karl on this occasion got scuttled by the Kings minority owners over financial concerns.<ref name=\"Kings-fire-Karl\">{{cite news|last=Stein|first=Marc|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/15203663/sacramento-kings-fire-coach-george-karl|title=Kings fire George Karl|agency=[[ESPN.com]]|date=April 14, 2016|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> Month and a half later, in late March 2016, Divac signed a multi-year contract extension with the organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/15097196/sacramento-kings-extend-contract-vp-vlade-divac |title=Kings extend contract of VP Vlade Divac |publisher=[[ESPN.com]] |date=March 30, 2016 |author=Marc Stein|author-link=Marc Stein (reporter) }}</ref> The team finished the season 33\u201349, eight games out of the playoffs, good for 10th spot in the Western Conference. Their final season in [[Sleep Train Arena]], the team's home since 1988, it was also their first 30 plus win campaign after seven consecutive seasons of fewer than 30 wins.\n\nEarly into the team's off-season, in mid April 2016, the Kings organization fired head coach George Karl, a decision made by Divac who had reportedly been pushing for it for months.<ref name=\"Kings-fire-Karl\"/> Within three weeks, during which Divac interviewed head coaching candidates [[Sam Mitchell (basketball)|Sam Mitchell]], [[Vinny Del Negro]], [[Mike Woodson]], [[David Blatt]], [[Mark Jackson (basketball)|Mark Jackson]], [[Jeff Hornacek]], [[Nate McMillan]], [[Patrick Ewing]], [[Elston Turner]], and [[Corliss Williamson]],<ref name=\"Joerger-hired\">{{cite news|author=ESPN.com news services|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/15494387/sacramento-kings-dave-joerger-agree-four-year-deal|title=Dave Joerger agrees to four-year deal to coach Kings|agency=[[ESPN.com]]|date=May 10, 2016|accessdate=June 23, 2018}}</ref> the Kings hired [[Dave Joerger]] as their new head coach, signing him to a four-year deal worth [[US$]]16 million.<ref name=\"Joerger-hired\"/> At the [[2016 NBA draft]], with the 8th pick, the Kings selected [[Marquese Chriss]] out of the [[Washington Huskies men's basketball|University of Washington]], but traded him to the [[Phoenix Suns]] for rights to [[Bogdan Bogdanovi\u0107 (basketball)|Bogdan Bogdanovi\u0107]] as well as the Suns' 2016 draft 13th and 28th picks, [[Georgios Papagiannis]] and [[Skal Labissi\u00e8re]], respectively.\n\nAt the [[2017 NBA draft]], with the 5th pick, the Kings selected point guard [[De'Aaron Fox]] out of [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]].\n\n==Investments==\nDivac has been involved in many non-basketball endeavors while still actively playing in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]], and more so after he retired. He is an active restaurant investor in the [[Sacramento, California]] area. However, his attempts to make major investments in Serbia failed, for a variety of reasons.\n\nThe most notable affair was a highly publicized business venture\u2014takeover bid of profitable beverage producer [[Knjaz Milo\u0161]]. Divac's company \"Apurna\", in a joint venture with French dairy giant [[Danone]], ostensibly proposed the best bid, but the takeover was aborted by the Serbia's Securities Commission, because Danone/Apurna allegedly offered extra money to small shareholders.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cee-foodindustry.com/news/ng.asp?id=56547&n=wh49&c=%23emailcode |title=Knjaz Milos auction descends into chaos |publisher=CEE-foodindustry.com |date=December 3, 2004 |accessdate=September 25, 2007 |author=Chris Mercer}}</ref>\nIn the repeated bid, Divac and Danone eventually withdrew and the sale went to [[FPP Balkan Ltd.]], a privatization fund from the [[Cayman Islands]]. The entire messy affair caused great friction within the [[Serbian government]], wide speculation about corruption, resignation of the Securities Commission chief, and even a police investigation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cee-foodindustry.com/news/ng.asp?id=56659-danone-pulls-out |title=Danone pulls out of Serbian soft drink bidding race |publisher=CEE-foodindustry.com |date=December 8, 2004 |accessdate=September 25, 2007 |author=Chris Mercer}}</ref>\n\nAnother similar, though less spectacular, episode happened with 2005 Divac's attempt to take over the ''[[Ve\u010dernje novosti]]'', a Serbian high-circulation daily.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dr\u017eava preigrala Divca |url=http://www.nuns.org.yu/dosije/18/10.jsp |author=Vera Didanovi\u0107 |publisher=nuns.org |date=January 3, 2006 |accessdate=July 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091228181340/http://www.nuns.org.yu/dosije/18/10.jsp |archivedate=December 28, 2009 |df= }}</ref> He made an agreement with small shareholders to take over the company by means of registering a new company with joint capital, which would increase the share capital. However, the Serbian Government intervened and halted what should have been a mere technical move.  While the attempted takeover was a \"backdoor\" one indeed, it was legal and similar cases had already occurred. The government ostensibly feared lack of control over the influential daily. Even though the [[Supreme Court of Serbia]] eventually ruled in Divac's favor, he withdrew from the contest, citing \"friendly advice\" by unnamed persons.<ref>{{cite web |title=NBA ace Vlade Divac slam dunks the Serbian government |url=http://www.setimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/en_GB/features/setimes/features/2006/07/06/feature-02 |author=Georgi Mitev-Shantek |publisher=Southeast European Times |date=July 6, 2006 |accessdate=September 25, 2007}}</ref> Embittered, he decided to stop his attempts to invest in Serbia: \"All of this is ugly and I'm very upset... I realized that there's no place for me in Serbia and my friends can meet me in Madrid from now on... In Serbia, some different rules are in effect, and I can't conceive them\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dnevnik.rs/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=12484 |title=Vuk\u010devi\u0107: Dijaspora \u0107e zapamtiti kako je pro\u0161ao Divac |publisher=[[Dnevnik (Novi Sad)]] |language=Serbian |date=July 21, 2006 |accessdate=September 25, 2007 |author=Lj. Male\u0161evi\u0107}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nHowever, that turned out not to be true, as in October 2007 Divac got legally registered as 100% owner of [[Voda Voda]], a [[bottled water]] brand previously owned by businessman [[Vojin \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107]]. That transaction was also followed by a stir of controversy, as \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107 publicly accused Divac of deceit, asserting that he broke a [[gentlemen's agreement]] they had, and questioning the validity of the contract that Divac presented to the [[Serbian Business Registers Agency]]. The circumstances surrounding the deal (as of November 2007) are still unclear: Divac claims that he indeed loaned some money to the \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107's [[Si&Si]] company, which was in financial troubles, and after \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107 failed to fulfill his part of the deal, just used the contract, already properly signed by \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107, to claim ownership of the company.<ref name=\"politika\">{{cite web |url=http://www.blic.co.rs/infocus.php?id=947 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130416121130/http://www.blic.co.rs/infocus.php?id=947 |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 16, 2013 |title=You are insulting me while you have debts |date=October 31, 2007 |publisher=[[Blic]] |accessdate=November 5, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"b92voda\">{{cite web |url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/business-article.php?yyyy=2007&mm=11&dd=02&nav_id=45059 |title=Government to intervene in Voda Voda feud |date=November 2, 2007 |publisher=[[B92]] |accessdate=November 5, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107103443/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/business-article.php?yyyy=2007&mm=11&dd=02&nav_id=45059 |archivedate=November 7, 2007 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Humanitarian work==\n[[Image:Vlade Divac.jpg|thumb|right|235px|Vlade Divac (rear, center) alongside Crown Prince [[Alexander, Crown Prince of Yugoslavia|Alexander II]] in 2005, at an event for [[World Heart Federation|World Heart Day]]]]\nDivac is a humanitarian worker, focusing on aid to children worldwide and refugees in his home country. Along with six Serbian basketball teammates, Divac established the charity called [[Group Seven]], later renamed to \"Divac's Children Foundation\", and works closely with [[International Orthodox Christian Charities]] (IOCC), helping them to raise around US$500,000 for humanitarian assistance in Serbia since 1997.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://divac.com/aboutus.html |title=About us |publisher=Divac's Children Foundation |accessdate=September 25, 2007}}</ref> Divac's own foundation, presided by his wife Sne\u017eana, provided over $2,500,000 in humanitarian assistance through 1998\u20132007.<ref name=\"nba\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/news/divac_youcantoo_070922.html |title=Divac Creates New Team With \"You Can Too\" Campaign |publisher=[[NBA.com]] |date=September 22, 2007 |accessdate=September 25, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011022055/http://www.nba.com/news/divac_youcantoo_070922.html |archive-date=October 11, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn late 2007 Divac founded a humanitarian organization, \"You Can Too\" ([[Serbian language|Serbian]]: ''\u041c\u043e\u0436\u0435\u0448 \u0438 \u0442\u0438/Mo\u017ee\u0161 i ti''), bent on assisting the refugees in Serbia. Serbia has around 500,000 refugees from the 1990s [[Yugoslav wars]], making it the country with the largest refugee problem in Europe.<ref name=\"nba\" />  Around 7,800 of those people still live in collective centers under poor conditions, so the organization has vouched itself to buy abandoned countryside houses, in an attempt to finally solve their accommodation problem.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.b92.net/sport/kosarka/kosarka.php?yyyy=2007&mm=09&dd=21&nav_id=264626 |title=Divac za 7.850 izbeglica |publisher=[[B92]] |language=Serbian |date=September 23, 2007 |accessdate=September 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\nFrom September 21 to 23, 2007, Divac organized an official farewell from active basketball career in his hometown Prijepolje and Belgrade, simultaneously promoting the \"You Can Too\" campaign. The spectacle culminated in gathering of Divac and his worldwide friends in front of 10,000 people outside the [[National Assembly of Serbia|National Assembly]] building.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.b92.net/sport/kosarka/kosarka.php?yyyy=2007&mm=09&dd=23&nav_id=264726 |title=Spektakularni opro\u0161taj Divca |publisher=[[B92]] |language=Serbian |date=September 23, 2007 |accessdate=September 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nIn the early 1990s, the song \"Vlade Divac\" by Belgrade band [[Deca Lo\u0161ih Muzi\u010dara]], devoted to his transfer to Lakers, was a big hit; the band finally got to personally meet Divac and perform the song with him on his farewell party in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://arhiva.kurir-info.rs/Arhiva/2007/septembar/22/ST-06-22092007.shtml |title=Deca Lo\u0161ih Muzi\u010dara pevaju za Divca! |publisher=[[Kurir]] |date=September 22, 2007 |accessdate=September 25, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDuring his time with the Lakers, Divac's popularity and marketing potential, in addition to his entertaining and good-natured personality, were picked up on by the American TV industry. As a result, he appeared quite a few times on Los Angeles-based late night programmes such as ''[[The Arsenio Hall Show]]'' and ''[[The Tonight Show with Jay Leno]]''. In 1990, he was featured in a commercial with Laker teammates [[A. C. Green]] and [[Mychal Thompson]] for the [[Schick (razors)|Schick]] brand razors company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bCTx6K3Irag |title=1990 \u2013 Schick \u2013 Vlade Divac, A.C. Green, Mychal Thompson |publisher=YouTube |date=September 5, 2008 |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> He also appeared in American [[sitcom]]s ''[[Married... with Children]]'' and ''[[Coach (TV series)|Coach]]'', as well as in the short lived ''[[Good Sports]]'' sitcom. On the big screen Divac took part in basketball-based movies ''[[Eddie (film)|Eddie]]'', ''[[Space Jam]]'' and ''[[Juwanna Mann]]''. Later in his career, he appeared on ''[[Larry King Live]]'' in 1999 and ''[[The Late Late Show (CBS TV series)|The Late Late Show]]'' in 2002.\n\nIn Serbia, all throughout his playing career, Divac regularly appeared in commercials pitching products ranging from Atlas Beer to [[OTP banka Srbija a.d.|Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 G\u00e9n\u00e9rale]] mortgage credit plans. He appeared in a national TV commercial in the United States alongside former NBA star [[Darryl Dawkins]] for [[Taco Bell]].\n\nDivac appeared as a special guest on [[Eurovision Song Contest 2008|Eurovision 2008]]. He threw a ball into the audience, which marked the beginning of [[televoting]].\n\nDivac features in the [[ESPN]] ''[[30 for 30]]'' documentary ''[[Once Brothers]]'', where he discusses the exploits of the [[Yugoslavia national basketball team]] in the late 1980s and early 1990s and how the Yugoslav Wars tore them apart, especially in context of his broken friendship with Croatian player [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]].<ref name=once/>\n\nDivac appears in [[Boris Malagurski]]'s documentary film ''[[The Weight of Chains]]'', in which he talks about the 1999 [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]].\n\n==Personal life==\nDivac and his wife, Sne\u017eana, have two sons, Luka and Matija, and an adopted daughter, Petra, whose biological parents were killed.<ref name=\"si-may1999-Rick Reilly\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Movies===\n* ''Driving Me Crazy'' (1991) \u2013 Yugo Boss\n* ''[[Eddie (film)|Eddie]]'' (1996) \u2013 Himself (Los Angeles Lakers)\n* ''[[Space Jam]]'' (1996) \u2013 Himself (Los Angeles Lakers)\n* ''Driving Me Crazy'' (TV) (2000) \u2013 Viglione, Gene\n* ''[[Juwanna Mann]]'' (2002) \u2013 beat player Morse\n* ''Crossover'' (2004) \u2013 Himself\n* ''A3 - Rock'n'Roll uzvraca udarac'' (2006) \u2013 Pretpostavljeni\n* ''We are No Angels 3: Rock & Roll Fight Back'' (2008) \u2013 God\n* ''[[The Weight of Chains]]'' (2010) \u2013 Himself ([[documentary]] interview)\n\n===Television===\n* ''[[Once Brothers]]'' \u2013 ESPN documentary about Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107 and Vlade Divac\n* ''[[Good Sports]]'', \"The Reviews are in\" (1991) \u2013 Himself\n* ''[[Coach (TV series)|Coach]]'', \"Dateline-Bangkok\" (1992) \u2013 delivery man\n* ''[[Married... with Children]]'', episode \"A Tisket, a Tasket, Can Peg Make a Basket?\" 